<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="112" name="Mineral Nutrition">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Hydroponics is defined as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Growing plants in nutrient solution without soil</option><option id="B">Soil-less gardening with air</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Developed by Julius von Sachs (1860).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Essential elements must be ____ for normal growth and reproduction.</text>
            <option id="A">Irreplaceable</option><option id="B">Variable</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Second criterion of essentiality.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Macronutrients are required in amounts ____ 10 mmole/kg of dry matter.</text>
            <option id="A">Greater than</option><option id="B">Less than</option><option id="C">Exactly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes C, H, O, N, P, K, S, Ca, Mg.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Micronutrients are required in amounts ____ 10 mmole/kg of dry matter.</text>
            <option id="A">Less than</option><option id="B">Greater than</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trace elements like Fe, Mn, Cu, Mo, Zn, B, Cl, Ni.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is NOT a macronutrient?</text>
            <option id="A">Manganese (Mn)</option><option id="B">Nitrogen (N)</option><option id="C">Phosphorus (P)</option><option id="D">Sulfur (S)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mn is a micronutrient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogen is absorbed mainly as ____ ions.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrate (NO3-)</option><option id="B">Ammonium (NH4+)</option><option id="C">Nitrite (NO2-)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Primary form of N uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phosphorus is a constituent of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cell membranes, Nucleic acids, and ATP</option><option id="B">Cellulose only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vital for energy and genetics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium (K) helps in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Anion-cation balance and stomatal opening</option><option id="B">Giving red color</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly mobile ion in plants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Calcium is required during ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cell division (middle lamella formation)</option><option id="B">At night only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Required as calcium pectate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnesium is the central atom of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorophyll</option><option id="B">Hemoglobin</option><option id="C">ATP</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial for photosynthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sulfur is present in which two amino acids?</text>
            <option id="A">Cysteine and Methionine</option><option id="B">Glycine and Alanine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Building blocks of proteins.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Iron (Fe) is absorbed as ____ ions.</text>
            <option id="A">Ferric (Fe3+)</option><option id="B">Ferrous (Fe2+)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Needed in larger amounts than other micros.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Manganese is involved in ____ during photosynthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Splitting of water (Photolysis)</option><option id="B">CO2 fixation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Releases oxygen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Zinc (Zn) is needed for the synthesis of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Auxin (Plant hormone)</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specifically IAA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Boron (B) is required for ____ growth.</text>
            <option id="A">Pollen tube</option><option id="B">Root hair only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also for Ca2+ uptake and carbohydrate translocation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molybdenum (Mo) is a component of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrogenase and Nitrate reductase</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vital for Nitrogen metabolism.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Appearance of deficiency symptoms in older regular tissues means element is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Highly mobile (N, P, K, Mg)</option><option id="B">Immobile</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transported from old to new parts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Deficiency symptoms appearing first in younger leaves means element is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Immobile (Ca, S)</option><option id="B">Mobile</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fixed in structure (e.g. wall).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorosis is the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Loss of chlorophyll (yellowing)</option><option id="B">Death of tissue</option><option id="C">Leaf fall</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common deficiency symptom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Necrosis is the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Death of tissue (spots/patches)</option><option id="B">Yellowing</option><option id="C">Swelling</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Typically caused by lack of Ca, Mg, Cu, K.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Delayed flowering is caused by low ____.</text>
            <option id="A">N, S, Mo</option><option id="B">Ca, P</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific metabolic inhibition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Toxicity of Manganese can cause ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Fe, Mg, Ca</option><option id="B">N, P</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Competitive inhibition of uptake/binding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogen fixation is the process of converting ____ to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">N2 to Ammonia (NH3)</option><option id="B">Nitrate to N2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Biological or industrial process.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>An example of free-living nitrogen fixing bacteria is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Azotobacter</option><option id="B">Rhizobium</option><option id="C">Cyanobacteria only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also Beijerinckia.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rhizobium forms symbiotic association with ____ plants.</text>
            <option id="A">Leguminous</option><option id="B">Cereal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Nodules on roots.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pink color of root nodules is due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Leg-hemoglobin</option><option id="B">Anthocyanin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxygen scavenger protein.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The enzyme responsible for nitrogen fixation is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrogenase</option><option id="B">Nitrate reductase</option><option id="C">Peptidase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains Mo-Fe protein.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogenase is highly sensitive to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molecular oxygen (O2)</option><option id="B">Nitrogen</option><option id="C">Temperature</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires anaeroabic conditions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Synthesis of amino acids from ammonia occurs via ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Reductive amination and Transamination</option><option id="B">Photosynthesis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Key metabolic paths.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amides like Asparagine contain ____ nitrogen than amino acids.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option><option id="C">Equal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for long distance N transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of a non-leguminous plant that forms nodules is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alnus (via Frankia)</option><option id="B">Gram</option><option id="C">Pea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actinomycete symbiosis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Biological nitrogen fixation requires ____ ATP per NH3 molecule.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">16</option><option id="C">2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High energy cost process.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>N2 + 8e- + 8H+ + ____ ATP -&gt; 2NH3 + H2.</text>
            <option id="A">16</option><option id="B">8</option><option id="C">4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>8 ATP per ammonia produced.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Process of nitrate reduction was first done in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cytoplasm</option><option id="B">Mitochondria</option><option id="C">Soil</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via nitrate reductase enzyme.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first stable product of N2 fixation is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammonia (NH3)</option><option id="B">Nitrite</option><option id="C">Amino acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Instantly converted to NH4+ for use.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Essentiality can be checked by ____ method.</text>
            <option id="A">Nutrient-omission experiment</option><option id="B">Burning</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Identify specific deficiency symptoms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of elements found in different plants so far is over ____.</text>
            <option id="A">60</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">10</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only 17 are considered absolutely essential.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Beneficial elements (not essential for all) include ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Na, Si, Co, Se</option><option id="B">Fe, Cu</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Especially for higher plants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Elements which are part of biomolecules are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Structural elements (C, H, O, N)</option><option id="B">Catalytic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Framework of life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inhibition of cell division is caused by lack of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">N, K, S, Mo</option><option id="B">Ca, Mg</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stunted growth symptom.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Toxicity occurs when dry weight is reduced by ____ percent.</text>
            <option id="A">10</option><option id="B">50</option><option id="C">100</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Definition of critical toxicity level.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Uptake of ions involves inward move called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Influx</option><option id="B">Efflux</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually active across endodermis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Outward movement of ions is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Efflux</option><option id="B">Influx</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often passive but can be regulated.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first phase of ion uptake is ____ and occurs into ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Passive, Apoplast</option><option id="B">Active, Symplast</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rapid initial uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The second phase of ion uptake is ____ and occurs into ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Active, Symplast</option><option id="B">Passive, Apoplast</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Metabolic energy required.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mineral salts are translocated through ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xylem</option><option id="B">Phloem only</option><option id="C">Stomata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Follows the transpiration stream.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Soil provides minerals primarily through ____ of rocks.</text>
            <option id="A">Weathering</option><option id="B">Photosynthesis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Release of inorganic ions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ammonification is the conversion of ____ to ammonia.</text>
            <option id="A">Organic nitrogen (dead matter)</option><option id="B">Atmospheric N2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Part of Nitrogen cycle.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrification involves conversion of NH3 to ____ then ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrite (NO2-), Nitrate (NO3-)</option><option id="B">Nitrate, N2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bacterial oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrosomonas converts ammonia to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrite (NO2-)</option><option id="B">Nitrate</option><option id="C">N2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chemoautotrophic bacteria.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrobacter converts nitrite to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrate (NO3-)</option><option id="B">Ammonia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Second step of nitrification.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Denitrification is the conversion of nitrate to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrogen gas (N2)</option><option id="B">Ammonia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Performed by Pseudomonas and Thiobacillus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The site of nitrogen fixation in leguminous roots is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nodule</option><option id="B">Leaf</option><option id="C">Cortex air space</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specifically within infected cortical cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Leg-hemoglobin regulates ____ concentration to protect nitrogenase.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen</option><option id="B">Nitrogen</option><option id="C">Hydrogen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Creates micro-aerobic environment.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reductive amination uses ____ as the substrate.</text>
            <option id="A">Alpha-ketoglutaric acid</option><option id="B">Succinic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Converts to Glutamic acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transfer of amino group from one AA to keto acid is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transamination</option><option id="B">Deamination</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mediated by transaminase enzymes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ureides are transported N forms in ____ plant.</text>
            <option id="A">Soybean</option><option id="B">Wheat</option><option id="C">Pea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Low C:N ratio transport units.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is associated with opening of stomata?</text>
            <option id="A">Potassium (K+)</option><option id="B">Magnesium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regulates turgidity of guard cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is a part of biotin and Coenzyme A?</text>
            <option id="A">Sulfur (S)</option><option id="B">Phosphorus</option><option id="C">Nitrogen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vitamin/enzyme role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Interveinal chlorosis is usually a sign of ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Fe or Mg</option><option id="B">Ca</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common diagnostic symptom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Anion uptake is often driven by electrical gradient created by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">H+ pump (ATPase)</option><option id="B">Gravity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Primary active transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Critical concentration is the level ____ which plant growth is retarded.</text>
            <option id="A">Below</option><option id="B">Above</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Deficiency threshold.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solution culture is used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Commercial production of tomatoes and cucumbers</option><option id="B">Farming trees</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficient hydroponic systems.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plants obtain Nitrogen from ____, but bacteria help from ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Soil (Nitrate), Atmosphere (N2)</option><option id="B">Air, Soil</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Different N pools.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rhizobia are ____ before invasion of root hairs.</text>
            <option id="A">Free-living rod shaped bacteria</option><option id="B">Obligate parasites</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transition to symbiotic bacteroids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Infection thread carries bacteria to the ____ of the root.</text>
            <option id="A">Cortex</option><option id="B">Xylem</option><option id="C">Epidermis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leads to nudge of cortical cell division.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lehemoglobin is produced by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Partnership (plant DNA for heme? No. Plant Globin, Rhizobium Heme)</option><option id="B">Only Rhizobium</option><option id="C">Only Plant</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Joint symbiotic effort.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which mineral is essential for water splitting? (Multiple choice check)</text>
            <option id="A">Mn and Cl</option><option id="B">Fe and Cu</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Components of Oxygen Evolving Complex.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogen is required by plants in ____ amount compared to other minerals.</text>
            <option id="A">Greatest</option><option id="B">Smallest</option><option id="C">Equal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highest percentage of dry matter after C, O, H.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnesium is an activator of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RuBisCO and PEPcase</option><option id="B">Nitrogenase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Central for photosynthetic carbon cycle.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Essentiality check: Element must be directly involved in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Metabolism</option><option id="B">Only looks</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Final criterion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>How can we check if an element is essential for a specific plant?</text>
            <option id="A">Purified water and mineral salts with omission of one element</option><option id="B">Boiling it</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydroponics technique usage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Criteria for essentiality were given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Arnon and Stout</option><option id="B">Munch</option><option id="C">Priestley</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Established in 1939.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element activates Alcohol dehydrogenase?</text>
            <option id="A">Zinc (Zn)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">Copper</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural/cofactor role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Maintenance of cell turgidity involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorine and Potassium</option><option id="B">Silicon</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Osmotic regulation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Little leaf disease is caused by ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Zinc (Zn)</option><option id="B">Nitrogen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Associated with auxin deficiency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Grey spots on oats are due to ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Manganese (Mn)</option><option id="B">Boron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific crop-mineral match.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Whiptail disease in cauliflower is due to ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Molybdenum (Mo)</option><option id="B">Zinc</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Restricts leaf blade development.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Heart rot of sugar beet is due to ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Boron (B)</option><option id="B">Potassium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known Boron symptom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Toxicity is hard to identify because it often induces ____ of other elements.</text>
            <option id="A">Deficiency</option><option id="B">Excess</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Indirect effects.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Brown spots surrounded by chlorotic veins is character of ____ toxicity.</text>
            <option id="A">Manganese (Mn)</option><option id="B">Iron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classic toxicity symptom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogenase converts N2 to NH3 via addition of ____ protons and electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">8 and 8</option><option id="B">6 and 6</option><option id="C">2 and 2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on equation balance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Biological N2 fixation is inhibited by ____ even in trace amounts.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen</option><option id="B">CO2</option><option id="C">Water</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Must maintain anaerobiosis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rhizobium bacteroids are ____ in shape.</text>
            <option id="A">Irregular / Pleomorphic</option><option id="B">Perfect circles</option><option id="C">Long fibers</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Differentiated internal cell forms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Atmospheric N2 contains a ____ bond between N atoms.</text>
            <option id="A">Triple (N≡N)</option><option id="B">Double</option><option id="C">Single</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Makes N2 very stable/inert.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nodule formation involves ____ of root hairs.</text>
            <option id="A">Curling</option><option id="B">Straightening</option><option id="C">Breaking</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Induced by bacterial signals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first step in nitrogen cycle after synthesis is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Assimilation by bacteria / plants</option><option id="B">Escaping to space</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Entry into food chain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Element required for stability of structural elements but not mobile is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium (Ca)</option><option id="B">Potassium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural integrity role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes 'Active transport' into symplast?</text>
            <option id="A">High affinity, saturatable, energy dependent</option><option id="B">Unlimited, passive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mediated by membrane proteins.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Function of 'Cytochromes' involves which metal ion transition?</text>
            <option id="A">Fe2+ to Fe3+</option><option id="B">Mg2+</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electron transport role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Excess Mn inhibits which metabolic path of Magnesium?</text>
            <option id="A">Enzyme binding in chlorophyll synthesis</option><option id="B">Water uptake</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Compete for identical binding sites.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nodules have direct connect with ____ of host for nutrient exchange.</text>
            <option id="A">Vascular tissue (Xylem/Phloem)</option><option id="B">Only epidermis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vascular strands connect to nodule.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The primary role of Molybdenum in plants is related to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Assimilation of nitrogen</option><option id="B">Cell wall</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cofactor for nitrate reductase.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorosis of older leaves in Nitrogen deficiency is due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">N being mobile</option><option id="B">N being immobile</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resources pulled to growing tips.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Necrosis in Ca deficiency occurs in younger leaves because ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ca is immobile</option><option id="B">Ca is mobile</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot be exported from old tissues.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is associated with synthesis of chlorophyll precursors?</text>
            <option id="A">Iron (Fe)</option><option id="B">Boron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Not in chlorophyll but needed for its making.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plants like Venus flytrap are ____ autotrophs.</text>
            <option id="A">Partial (Photosynthetic but Nitrogen heterotrophs)</option><option id="B">Complete</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adaptation to N-poor soil.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of ions across membrane proteins against gradient is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pump mediated transport</option><option id="B">Channel flow</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific ATPase / Antiport mechanisms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is needed for middle lamella of cell walls?</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium (Ca)</option><option id="B">Silicon</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>As calcium pectate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium-Malate accumulation in guard cells is ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Osmotically active</option><option id="B">Neutral</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Drives water in.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sulphur deficiency results in ____ flowering.</text>
            <option id="A">Delayed</option><option id="B">Early</option><option id="C">Red</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Metabolic stall symptom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Isotope N-15 can be used to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Trace nitrogen movement in cycle</option><option id="B">Stop fixation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heavy isotope tracer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of elements necessary for HIGHER plants (beneficial ones):</text>
            <option id="A">4 (Na, Si, Co, Se)</option><option id="B">10</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often mentioned in advanced texts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can organic molecules be absorbed as N source?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes, by some plants (Insectivorous)</option><option id="B">No, only ions</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exception to standard ion uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Element which maintains ribosome structure is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg)</option><option id="B">Calcium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specifically dimerizes subunits.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is key for Redox reactions in photsynthesis and respiration?</text>
            <option id="A">Copper (Cu)</option><option id="B">Boron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Present in plastocyanin and cytochrome c oxidase.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dieback of shoots is a symptom of ____ deficiency.</text>
            <option id="A">Copper (Cu)</option><option id="B">Zinc</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Severe developmental failure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Process of nitrate reduction consumes ____ electrons per nitrate.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NO3- (OS +5) to NH3 (OS -3). Difference is 8.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is Nitrogenase ATP-driven?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Essential for breaking N triple bond)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extremely high energy barrier.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>One mole of N2 produces ____ moles of ammonia.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass balance from stoichiometry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Soil solution has low concentration of P. Uptake is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Active</option><option id="B">Passive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic of essential nutrient entry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chelating agents like EDTA are used in nutrient solutions to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prevent mineral precipitation (especially Iron)</option><option id="B">Kill bacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Keep micronutrients available.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The critical concentration varies for different ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Elements</option><option id="B">Times of day only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Plant-specific requirement.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Element which activates Carboxylase in photosynthesis is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg)</option><option id="B">Iron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Central for enzymatic action.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check: Mineral nutrition count reached 120?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
